{"slug": "elixir", "root": "elixir", "category": "alchemy", "gloss": "a life-giving/perfecting draught", "definition": "An elixir is a perfecting or life-giving preparation — in alchemy the very agent of transmutation, the philosophers' stone in liquid form, and by extension the draught of health or immortality.", "history": "*Elixir* comes through Medieval Latin from Arabic *al-iksīr*, 'the philosophers' stone,' itself likely from Greek *xērion*, a 'drying powder' for wounds — so the word climbs from a medical powder to the transmuting stone to the water of eternal life. That *al-* is the Arabic article, as in *alchemy* and *alcohol*. Magic uses 'Elixir' for life-giving artifacts.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Etymonline, s.v. elixir", "where": "Etymology reference"}, {"label": "Lyndy Abraham, A Dictionary of Alchemical Imagery", "where": "Alchemy (PDF)", "url": "https://www.cambridge.org/us/universitypress/subjects/literature/english-literature-general-interest/dictionary-alchemical-imagery", "url_kind": "publisher", "abstract": "A reference book that decodes the strange symbols alchemists used, like the \"green lion\" or the \"philosopher's stone,\" explaining both their literal meaning as steps in a chemical process and the spiritual meaning that writers and poets later gave them, illustrated with historical woodcuts and engravings."}], "commentary": null, "commentary_sources": [], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"origin": "Medieval Latin ← Arabic al-iksīr ‘the philosopher’s stone’ ← Greek xērion ‘drying powder’", "first": "mid-14c.", "note": "Began as a dry medicinal powder for wounds, became the transmuting ‘stone,’ then the draught of eternal life.", "hook": "How wound-powder became the water of immortality.", "lang": "Arabic"}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_to